    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-09-12T09:05:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-09-12T09:05:00-05:00" n="230"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d230">
                <head>230. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Jordan</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d230fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, AV 12 <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss>. Confidential; Flash. It was repeated to
                        Athens (Immediate), Ankara, Beirut, Bonn, Bern, CINCSTRIKE, DIA, Dhahran,
                        Frankfurt, Nicosia, The Hague, London, Paris, Rome, Tel Aviv, Geneva, and
                        Zurich.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Amman</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-09-12T14:05:00+00:00">September 12, 1970,
                        1405Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4641. Dept pass Cairo Priority.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Rumors spreading at Intercontinental Hotel that all three planes have been
                        blown up after removing all passengers. British Embassy intelligence officer
                        states positively it is hard fact but has not revealed his source.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RA1">Rochat</persName> informed us 1535 local he had
                        just received phone call that <gloss target="#t_ICRC1">ICRC</gloss> convoy
                        on way to evacuate remaining group of male passengers had been halted by
                        fedayeen three kilometers from planes and told they would not be allowed to
                        proceed.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed> Brubeck</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
